title: For Sale/Trade:  Mida GIA Castelli. One is 1918 and one is 1925.
postcontent:
Mida GIA Castelli. One is 1918 and one is 1925. These were carried by Italian infantry.

Attention collectors, here is a WWl and WWll Revolver made by Castelli of Brescia Italy. The 10.4 mm cartridge (sometimes called the 10.35 mm) was made for the French Chamelot-Delvigne design Italian Model 1874 revolver. The Model 1889 is a descendent of the Model 1874 and was designed by Carlo Bode who in 1886 had obtained a patent for a revolver and it was intended as an improved version of the 1874. There were about 70 variants over its life time from 1889 until 1945 however there are three basic types, the “A” recognized by the folding trigger and the lack of a trigger guard, the “B” with a trigger guard and shorter (3 ½”) lighter round barrel version. There were both single action and double action versions.

This 6 shot revolver, widely known as “the bode,” has a 4 1/2” hexagonal barrel, fixed sights and is a double action. Mechanically this revolver is in pretty good condition, fully functional (loose), with a very good bore, deep rifling and no pitting or corrosion. The finish is mostly brown patina or bare metal and it has some dings and mars in the metal (see photos) but it is not a rust bucket. The checkered wood grips are in surprisingly good condition (see photos). The 10.4 mm cartridge is similar to the .44 Russian cartridge (see photos). The ammunition is still available in limited quantities from time to time from Foicchi. No ammunition is included in this auction, photos are for reference only.

title: For Sale:  Stoeger Cougar 9mm w/ 3 magazines -mint-
postcontent:
I have here a Stoeger Cougar in beautiful condition. Roughly 1000 rounds through it, religiously cleaned and cared for.

Shoots great, very accurate, light recoil, has a wonderful feel in the hand.

For those that don't know, Beretta developed the Cougar and released it just before polymer framed firearms hit the market. To answer the demand for a polymer framed handgun they took the guts and created the Beretta Storm. Later they transferred the tooling to Stoeger (all under the same umbrella). They have since made slight refinements to the design (more robust parts here and there, added rail, etc) and have kept a great gun on the market for relatively small cost.

I am selling it because I cannot find a Class 1 or Class 2 retention holster for it, and a holster of this type is required for a security position I am in.

I have the two 15rd magazines it came with, as well as 1 extra 15rd mag I purchased from Stoeger. Also have the original packaging and the plastic case with cleaning supplies and lock.
